Caesar: as proelor deszgnatus, he spoke after the consulars and before the praetorians. It is a missortune that Sallust’s vanity led him to compose —in the fashion of ancient historians—this arti- ficial speech, instead of preserving some of the notices which were probably extant, of what was really said. Caesar could hardly have uttered the stale commonplaces—-exactly in the style of Sallust, who is nothing if not general — with which this rhetorical exercise begins. But the sentiments and the temper are doubtless Caesar’s own, and the argument is substantially as Cicero reports it.
